lized": false, "mention": "BDNF-producing neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7609136700630188, "span": {"begin": 563, "end": 585}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BDNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8940825462341309, "span": {"begin": 563, "end": 567}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4915"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Trk-B", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9869086146354675, "span": {"begin": 610, "end": 615}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GABA PV-interneurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7436217069625854, "span": {"begin": 623, "end": 643}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BDNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9922425746917725, "span": {"begin": 723, "end": 727}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BDNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9911161661148071, "span": {"begin": 810, "end": 814}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hippocampal and neocortical interneurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8129628300666809, "span": {"begin": 874, "end": 914}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:627"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BDNF", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.984061062335968, "span": {"begin": 1001, "end": 1005}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005680"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GABA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9914675951004028, "span": {"begin": 1043, "end": 1047}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:29103"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "K(+)", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991879463195801, "span": {"begin": 1057, "end": 1061}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30120"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Cl(-)", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987272620201111, "span": {"begin": 1062, "end": 1067}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:57468"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "KCC2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5834059119224548, "span": {"begin": 1084, "end": 1088}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005680"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GABA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9993700385093689, "span": {"begin": 1128, "end": 1132}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005680"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "GABA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9997698664665222, "span": {"begin": 1213, "end": 1217}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "glutamatergic", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5826180577278137, "span": {"begin": 1241, "end": 1254}}], "text": "GABAergic interneurons are remarkably diverse and complex in nature and they are believed to play a key role in numerous neurodevelopmental processes (Southwell et al., 2014). Among them, those that express parvalbumin (PV) (marker of GABAergic interneurons) as their calcium-binding protein are the ones subjected to regulations by neurotrophins and BDNF specifically (Woo and Lu, 2006). These neurons do not express the BDNF protein but its functional receptor, Trk-B (Cellerino et al., 1996; Marty et al., 1996; Gorba and Wahle, 1999). BDNF is released by the BDNF-producing neurons of the CNS and binds to Trk-B of the GABA PV-interneurons, an interaction necessary for the subsequent developmental effects mediated by BDNF (Polleux et al., 2002; Jin et al., 2003; Rico et al., 2002; Aguado et al., 2003). BDNF promotes the morphological and neurochemical maturation of hippocampal and neocortical interneurons and promotes GABAergic synaptogenesis (Danglot et al., 2006 and Hu and Russek, 2008). BDNF also regulates the expression of the GABA-specific K(+)/Cl(-) co-transporter, KCC2, which is responsible for switching of GABA action from excitatory to inhibitory, and consequently determines the nature of GABA-induced development of glutamatergic (excitatory) synapses (Wang and Kriegstein, 2009; Blaesse et al., 2009).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:45:04 +0000 2026"}